{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}
In [[epistemology]], '''transparency''' is a property of epistemic [[State of being|states]] defined as follows: An epistemic state E is "weakly transparent" to a subject S [[if and only if]] when S is in state E, S can know that S is in state E; an epistemic state E is "strongly transparent" to a subject S if and only if when S is in state E, S can know that S is in state E, AND when S is not in state E, S can know S is not in state E.
[[Pain]] is usually considered to be strongly transparent: when someone is in pain, he knows immediately that he is in pain, and if he is not in pain, he will know he is not. Transparency is important in the study of [[Self-knowledge (psychology)|self-knowledge]] and [[meta-knowledge]].
==Sources== * Paul A. Boghossian, "The Transparency of Mental Content"; Philosophical Perspectives, Vol. 8, Logic and Language. (1994), pp.&nbsp;33–50.
